# Chainlit Setup And AWS Deployment Guide\par
\par
This document captures the end-to-end setup used in this workspace:\par
\par
- local Chainlit installation\par
- echo-mode validation\par
- OpenAI-backed responses\par
- AWS deployment on ECS Fargate\par
- Bedrock Knowledge Bases integration\par
\par
## 1. Local installation\par
\par
Open a terminal in the project root and run:\par
\par
```bash\par
pip install chainlit\par
chainlit hello\par
```\par
\par
If the hello app opens in the browser, Chainlit is installed correctly.\par
\par
For the latest development version from GitHub:\par
\par
```bash\par
pip install git+https://github.com/Chainlit/chainlit.git#subdirectory=backend/\par
```\par
\par
Note: the development version may require additional frontend tooling such as Node.js and pnpm.\par
\par
## 2. Minimal Chainlit app\par
\par
The project app lives in `demo.py`.\par
\par
Basic Chainlit pattern:\par
\par
```python\par
import chainlit as cl\par
\par
@cl.on_message\par
async def main(message: cl.Message):\par
    await cl.Message(content=f"You said: \{message.content\}").send()\par
```\par
\par
Run the app with:\par
\par
```bash\par
chainlit run demo.py --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000\par
```\par
\par
## 3. Echo-mode setup used here\par
\par
The current app was set up in two phases.\par
\par
First, echo mode was used to verify that:\par
\par
- the Chainlit server starts\par
- the browser can connect\par
- a submitted message reaches the Python handler\par
- the UI can render a response\par
\par
Echo mode is the fastest way to isolate transport issues from model issues.\par
\par
Current echo behavior:\par
\par
- if `OPENAI_API_KEY` is not set, the app replies with the user message\par
- it also explains that the app is still in echo mode\par
\par
Example behavior:\par
\par
```text\par
Echo mode: hello\par
\par
Set OPENAI_API_KEY to enable real model responses.\par
```\par
\par
## 4. OpenAI-backed setup used here\par
\par
The current `demo.py` supports two runtime modes:\par
\par
1. Echo fallback when `OPENAI_API_KEY` is missing\par
2. Real model responses when `OPENAI_API_KEY` is present\par
\par
Environment template in `.env.example`:\par
\par
```env\par
OPENAI_API_KEY=your_openai_api_key_here\par
OPENAI_MODEL=gpt-4.1-mini\par
```\par
\par
How the app works:\par
\par
- `on_chat_start` checks whether OpenAI is configured\par
- `on_message` falls back to echo mode if the API key is missing\par
- otherwise it calls the OpenAI Responses API and returns the model output\par
\par
To enable model responses locally:\par
\par
```bash\par
cp .env.example .env\par
```\par
\par
Then edit `.env` and set a real key.\par
\par
After that, restart the app:\par
\par
```bash\par
chainlit run demo.py --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000\par
```\par
\par
## 5. Why echo mode matters\par
\par
If the UI shows no answer at all, the problem is usually one of these:\par
\par
- the Chainlit server is not running\par
- the browser cannot connect back to the server\par
- the Python handler is not being triggered\par
- the app is waiting on an external model call that is failing\par
\par
Echo mode removes the external model dependency and proves the request path is working.\par
\par
## 6. Recommended AWS deployment method\par
\par
For a Chainlit app, the recommended AWS deployment path is:\par
\par
1. Containerize the app\par
2. Push the image to Amazon ECR\par
3. Run it on Amazon ECS Fargate\par
4. Expose it with an Application Load Balancer\par
5. Store secrets in AWS Secrets Manager\par
6. Use an ECS task role for Bedrock and other AWS access\par
\par
This is the preferred method because Chainlit is a long-running web app and benefits from a stable container runtime.\par
\par
## 7. Recommended AWS architecture\par
\par
```mermaid\par
flowchart LR\par
    U[Browser] --> ALB[Application Load Balancer]\par
    ALB --> ECS[ECS Fargate running Chainlit]\par
    ECS --> SM[Secrets Manager]\par
    ECS --> CW[CloudWatch Logs]\par
    ECS --> BKR[Bedrock Runtime]\par
    ECS --> KB[Bedrock Knowledge Base]\par
    KB --> OS[OpenSearch Serverless or vector store]\par
    KB --> S3[S3 source documents]\par
```\par
\par
## 8. Why ECS Fargate instead of Lambda\par
\par
Use ECS Fargate because:\par
\par
- Chainlit runs as a persistent web server\par
- websocket-like interaction patterns are easier behind an ALB\par
- container deployment is straightforward\par
- task roles make AWS integration cleaner\par
\par
Avoid Lambda for the main Chainlit UI server unless you are deliberately redesigning the app around a serverless pattern.\par
\par
## 9. Bedrock Knowledge Bases integration method\par
\par
The simplest reliable method is to query Bedrock Knowledge Bases from the Chainlit message handler.\par
\par
Preferred first implementation:\par
\par
- use `bedrock-agent-runtime`\par
- call `retrieve_and_generate`\par
- return the generated answer to Chainlit\par
\par
Example pattern:\par
\par
```python\par
import os\par
import boto3\par
\par
bedrock_agent = boto3.client(\par
    "bedrock-agent-runtime",\par
    region_name=os.environ.get("AWS_REGION", "us-east-1"),\par
)\par
\par
def ask_kb(user_query: str) -> str:\par
    response = bedrock_agent.retrieve_and_generate(\par
        input=\{"text": user_query\},\par
        retrieveAndGenerateConfiguration=\{\par
            "type": "KNOWLEDGE_BASE",\par
            "knowledgeBaseConfiguration": \{\par
                "knowledgeBaseId": os.environ["BEDROCK_KB_ID"],\par
                "modelArn": os.environ["BEDROCK_MODEL_ARN"],\par
            \},\par
        \},\par
    )\par
    return response["output"]["text"]\par
```\par
\par
Chainlit handler shape:\par
\par
```python\par
import chainlit as cl\par
\par
@cl.on_message\par
async def main(message: cl.Message):\par
    answer = ask_kb(message.content)\par
    await cl.Message(content=answer).send()\par
```\par
\par
## 10. AWS prerequisites for Bedrock KB\par
\par
Before deployment, create and validate:\par
\par
1. A Bedrock Knowledge Base\par
2. A data source for the KB\par
3. Ingested documents\par
4. A supported foundation model in the target region\par
5. An ECS task role with Bedrock permissions\par
\par
Environment variables to provide:\par
\par
```env\par
AWS_REGION=us-east-1\par
BEDROCK_KB_ID=your_kb_id\par
BEDROCK_MODEL_ARN=your_model_arn\par
```\par
\par
## 11. IAM permissions for the ECS task role\par
\par
Grant the ECS task role at least:\par
\par
- `bedrock:Retrieve`\par
- `bedrock:RetrieveAndGenerate`\par
- `bedrock:InvokeModel`\par
- `secretsmanager:GetSecretValue`\par
- `logs:CreateLogStream`\par
- `logs:PutLogEvents`\par
\par
If secrets are encrypted with a customer-managed KMS key, also allow KMS decrypt for that key.\par
\par
## 12. Containerization\par
\par
Example `Dockerfile`:\par
\par
```dockerfile\par
FROM python:3.12-slim\par
\par
WORKDIR /app\par
\par
COPY requirements.txt .\par
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt\par
\par
COPY . .\par
\par
EXPOSE 8000\par
\par
CMD ["chainlit", "run", "demo.py", "--host", "0.0.0.0", "--port", "8000"]\par
```\par
\par
Example `requirements.txt` for the AWS KB variant:\par
\par
```txt\par
chainlit\par
boto3\par
```\par
\par
If using OpenAI in the deployed version too:\par
\par
```txt\par
chainlit\par
boto3\par
openai\par
```\par
\par
## 13. ECS deployment steps\par
\par
1. Build the container image locally or in CI\par
2. Push it to Amazon ECR\par
3. Create an ECS task definition\par
4. Attach the task role with Bedrock permissions\par
5. Configure environment variables and Secrets Manager references\par
6. Create an ECS Fargate service\par
7. Attach the service to an ALB target group on port `8000`\par
8. Configure health checks on `/`\par
9. Review CloudWatch logs for startup and request handling\par
\par
Suggested starting capacity:\par
\par
- 0.5 vCPU\par
- 1 GB RAM\par
- 1 running task\par
\par
## 14. Networking guidance\par
\par
Recommended production layout:\par
\par
- public subnets for the ALB\par
- private subnets for ECS tasks\par
- NAT gateway or appropriate egress for AWS service access\par
\par
For a prototype, public tasks can work, but private tasks are the cleaner production approach.\par
\par
## 15. Secrets management\par
\par
Do not hardcode secrets in the repository.\par
\par
Use:\par
\par
- ECS task role for AWS credentials\par
- AWS Secrets Manager for non-AWS secrets\par
- environment variables for non-sensitive configuration\par
\par
For Bedrock usage inside ECS, prefer IAM task roles instead of static AWS access keys.\par
\par
## 16. Better RAG control pattern\par
\par
`retrieve_and_generate` is the fastest way to launch, but a more controllable pattern is:\par
\par
1. call `retrieve`\par
2. inspect or filter chunks\par
3. build your own prompt\par
4. call `bedrock-runtime`\par
5. return the answer with citations in Chainlit\par
\par
Use this pattern when you need stronger citation control, chunk inspection, or prompt customization.\par
\par
## 17. Practical rollout plan\par
\par
Recommended order of execution:\par
\par
1. Confirm echo mode locally\par
2. Confirm OpenAI mode locally\par
3. Replace the OpenAI path or add a Bedrock KB path\par
4. Containerize the app\par
5. Deploy to ECS Fargate\par
6. Validate ALB access and logs\par
7. Load test and refine task sizing\par
\par
## 18. Current workspace notes\par
\par
Current relevant local files:\par
\par
- `demo.py`\par
- `.env.example`\par
- `chainlit.md`\par
\par
The project also contains cloned upstream repositories under `Chainlit-org/`, but those are separate clones and not required for the local demo app itself.\par

